{
  "esm": "0.4.0",
  "metadata": {
    "name": "CloudChemistry",
    "description": "Full cloud chemistry system with pH computed from the electroneutrality condition — Seinfeld & Pandis (2006), Ch. 7. The model composes AqueousEquilibria (quadratic charge-balance H⁺ from dissolved CO2, SO2, NH3, HNO3, H2O2, and O3 equilibria) with SulfateFormation (S(IV) oxidation kinetics via O3, H2O2, and Fe/Mn pathways). Unlike CloudChemistryFixedpH, which prescribes H⁺ from an external pH_input, this model self-consistently solves for the cloud-water pH from the trace-gas composition. Migrated from Aerosol.jl@c8c640bb src/cloud_chemistry.jl:73.",
    "tags": [
      "aerosol",
      "cloud_chemistry",
      "aqueous_phase",
      "seinfeld_pandis_ch7",
      "charge_balance",
      "electroneutrality",
      "sulfate_formation",
      "composed"
    ],
    "created": "2026-05-30T00:00:00Z",
    "authors": [
      "Aerosol.jl contributors",
      "EarthSciModels migration (esm-33m)"
    ],
    "references": [
      {
        "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons. Chapter 7: Chemistry of the Atmospheric Aqueous Phase. Key sections: §7.3 (aqueous equilibria, Eqs. 7.10–7.61 and Table 7.4), §7.4 (rate conversions, Eqs. 7.75–7.78), §7.5 (S(IV) oxidation kinetics, Eqs. 7.79–7.102)."
      }
    ]
  },
  "models": {
    "CloudChemistry": {
      "reference": {
        "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons, Chapter 7.",
        "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1:src/cloud_chemistry.jl:73\n\nUpstream `CloudChemistry` (default instance name `:CloudChem`) is the full charge-balance variant of cloud chemistry from Seinfeld & Pandis (2006), Ch. 7. It instantiates two high-level subsystems: aq_eq (AqueousEquilibria — the full aqueous equilibrium system including the quadratic charge-balance for H⁺) and sulfate (SulfateFormation — S(IV) oxidation kinetics via O3, H2O2, and Fe/Mn-synergism pathways).\n\nKey difference from CloudChemistryFixedpH (src/cloud_chemistry.jl:269): instead of prescribing H⁺ from an external pH_input parameter, CloudChemistry computes H⁺ from the electroneutrality quadratic approximation within AqueousEquilibria:\n  H⁺ = √((K_w + K_c1·[CO2] + K_s1·[SO2] + K_n1·[HNO3] + K_h1·[H2O2]) / (1 + K_a1·[NH3]/K_w))\nThis couples the sulfate formation rates back to the actual aqueous pH, enabling self-consistent simulation of pH-sensitive chemistry.\n\nRe-typing: all input partial pressures and T are re-typed from parameter to state within the aq_eq subsystem because the parent coupling equations govern their values. L and xi_SO2 remain parameter type within the sulfate subsystem (consistent with CloudChemistryFixedpH precedent — they are calibration constants, not algebraic unknowns).\n\nAqueousEquilibria (aq_eq): flat composition of all aqueous equilibria (water, CO2, SO2, NH3, HNO3, H2O2, O3) with the quadratic charge-balance H⁺ computation. 43 equations, no sub-subsystems.\n\nSulfateFormation (sulfate): subsystem-composed model with 5 sub-subsystems (o3_ox, h2o2_ox, fe_ox, mn_ox, femn_ox) from sulfate/total.esm. R_total uses femn_ox.R_FeMn to avoid double-counting standalone fe_ox and mn_ox (upstream comment).\n\nTolerance rationale (rel=1e-6): purely algebraic, closed-form expressions including van't Hoff exp/log factors and polynomial rate laws. Matches AqueousEquilibria and SulfateFormation precedent."
      },
      "tolerance": {
        "rel": 1e-06
      },
      "variables": {
        "T": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "K",
          "default": 298.15,
          "description": "Cloud/air temperature. Drives van't Hoff corrections in the AqueousEquilibria subsystem and rate-conversion equations in SulfateFormation. Default 298.15 K (25°C)."
        },
        "p_CO2": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "Pa",
          "default": 38.5,
          "description": "Partial pressure of CO2. Default 38.5 Pa ≈ 380 ppm in 1 atm. Drives CO2 dissolution and carbonate equilibria in the aq_eq subsystem."
        },
        "p_SO2": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "Pa",
          "default": 0.000101325,
          "description": "Partial pressure of SO2. Default 1.01325e-4 Pa = 1 ppb in 1 atm. Drives SO2/S(IV) equilibria; the S(IV) species (SO2_aq, HSO3_minus, SO3_2minus) are the primary substrates for sulfate formation."
        },
        "p_NH3": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "Pa",
          "default": 0.000101325,
          "description": "Partial pressure of NH3. Default 1.01325e-4 Pa = 1 ppb. NH3 dissolves and forms NH4+, which is the main alkaline buffer in cloud water and raises pH relative to CO2-only conditions."
        },
        "p_HNO3": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "Pa",
          "default": 0.0,
          "description": "Partial pressure of HNO3. Default 0 Pa (no HNO3). HNO3 is a very strong acid (Ka >> 1) with a very large Henry's constant — even ppb levels strongly acidify cloud water. Set to a non-zero value to model HNO3 contributions to cloud acidity."
        },
        "p_H2O2": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "Pa",
          "default": 0.000101325,
          "description": "Partial pressure of H2O2. Default 1.01325e-4 Pa = 1 ppb. H2O2 is highly soluble (H_H2O2 ≈ 987 mol/m³/Pa) and is a major oxidant for the H2O2 sulfate-formation pathway."
        },
        "p_O3": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "Pa",
          "default": 0.005066,
          "description": "Partial pressure of O3. Default 5.066e-3 Pa ≈ 50 ppb. O3 is sparingly soluble and drives the O3 sulfate-formation pathway, which becomes important at high pH where SO3²- is abundant."
        },
        "Fe_III": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "default": 0.001,
          "description": "Fe(III) concentration in the cloud droplet. Default 1.0e-3 mol/m³ (1 µM). Catalyst for the Fe/Mn synergism S(IV) oxidation pathway (Eq. 7.102)."
        },
        "Mn_II": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "default": 0.001,
          "description": "Mn(II) concentration in the cloud droplet. Default 1.0e-3 mol/m³ (1 µM). Catalyst for the Fe/Mn synergism S(IV) oxidation pathway (Eq. 7.102)."
        },
        "L": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "g/m^3",
          "default": 0.5,
          "description": "Cloud liquid water content (g m⁻³). Default 0.5 g/m³, a representative stratocumulus value. Used in the SulfateFormation rate-conversion equations (Eqs. 7.75-7.78)."
        },
        "xi_SO2": {
          "type": "parameter",
          "units": "1",
          "default": 1e-09,
          "description": "Gas-phase SO2 mixing ratio (dimensionless mole fraction). Default 1.0e-9 (1 ppb). Used in the SulfateFormation %/hr rate conversion (Eq. 7.76) and SO2 lifetime (Eq. 7.78)."
        },
        "H_plus": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "description": "Hydrogen ion concentration, computed from the electroneutrality quadratic charge-balance in AqueousEquilibria: H⁺ = √((K_w + K_c1·[CO2] + K_s1·[SO2] + K_n1·[HNO3] + K_h1·[H2O2]) / (1 + K_a1·[NH3]/K_w)). This is the key difference from CloudChemistryFixedpH, which prescribes H⁺ from an external pH_input."
        },
        "OH_minus": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "description": "Hydroxide concentration, aliased from aq_eq.OH_minus = K_w(T) / H_plus."
        },
        "pH": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "1",
          "description": "pH value (dimensionless), aliased from aq_eq.pH = -log10(H_plus / C_ref)."
        },
        "SO2_aq": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "description": "Aqueous SO2 ([SO2·H2O]) concentration, aliased from aq_eq.SO2_aq = H_SO2(T) × p_SO2. Couples into the SulfateFormation subsystem for the O3 oxidation pathway."
        },
        "HSO3_minus": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "description": "Bisulfite [HSO3⁻] concentration, aliased from aq_eq.HSO3_minus. Dominates the S(IV) system at typical cloud pH (3–5). Couples into both O3 and H2O2 oxidation pathways."
        },
        "SO3_2minus": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "description": "Sulfite [SO3²⁻] concentration, aliased from aq_eq.SO3_2minus. Important for the O3 oxidation pathway due to the large k2 rate constant. Couples into the O3 oxidation pathway."
        },
        "H2O2_aq": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "description": "Aqueous H2O2 concentration, aliased from aq_eq.H2O2_aq = H_H2O2(T) × p_H2O2. H2O2 is highly soluble. Couples into the H2O2 oxidation pathway."
        },
        "O3_aq": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "description": "Aqueous O3 concentration, aliased from aq_eq.O3_aq = H_O3(T) × p_O3. O3 is sparingly soluble. Couples into the O3 oxidation pathway."
        },
        "S_IV_total": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3",
          "description": "Total S(IV) concentration (SO2_aq + HSO3_minus + SO3_2minus), aliased from aq_eq.S_IV_total. Used in the Fe/Mn synergism pathway."
        },
        "R_total": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3/s",
          "description": "Total S(IV) oxidation rate, aliased from sulfate.R_total = o3_ox.R_O3 + h2o2_ox.R_H2O2 + femn_ox.R_FeMn. The sum uses femn_ox (Eq. 7.102, includes Fe-only and Mn-only contributions) to avoid double-counting standalone fe_ox and mn_ox."
        },
        "R_O3": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3/s",
          "description": "S(IV) oxidation rate by O3, aliased from sulfate.o3_ox.R_O3. Eq. 7.79: R_O3 = (k0·[SO2·H2O] + k1·[HSO3⁻] + k2·[SO3²⁻])·[O3(aq)]. Increases strongly with pH."
        },
        "R_H2O2": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3/s",
          "description": "S(IV) oxidation rate by H2O2, aliased from sulfate.h2o2_ox.R_H2O2. Eq. 7.84: R_H2O2 = k·[H⁺]·[H2O2]·[HSO3⁻]/(1+K·[H⁺]). Often the dominant pathway in polluted cloud water."
        },
        "R_FeMn": {
          "type": "state",
          "units": "mol/m^3/s",
          "description": "S(IV) oxidation rate via Fe/Mn synergism, aliased from sulfate.femn_ox.R_FeMn. Eq. 7.102: includes Fe-only, Mn-only, and synergistic (k_FeMn = 1e10 M⁻²s⁻¹) terms."
        }
      },
      "subsystems": {
        "aq_eq": {
          "variables": {
            "T": {
              "type": "state",
              "units": "K",
              "default": 298.15,
              "description": "Temperature."
